1
00:00:00,020 --> 00:00:02,996
***Subtitles by Ardarvin & Mayumi***

2
00:00:03,020 --> 00:00:04,774
Let's move on to the next check.

3
00:00:04,799 --> 00:00:06,272
Here is the third check.

4
00:00:06,297 --> 00:00:11,019
Check 3: String Octet.

5
00:00:11,044 --> 00:00:16,349
Our octet is scored for four violins, and two violas and two cellos.

6
00:00:16,374 --> 00:00:20,100
Up to now, the highest total value of instruments on this show was...

7
00:00:20,180 --> 00:00:24,714
79.5 billion yen, featured last year.

8
00:00:24,740 --> 00:00:27,260
This time, we're going beyond that.

9
00:00:27,280 --> 00:00:33,141
We want you to savor an even more miraculous sound.

10
00:00:33,166 --> 00:00:41,415
The eight instruments in this octet have a record-breaking total value of 10.24 billion yen.

11
00:00:41,440 --> 00:00:44,310
So we've finally broken the 10-billion-yen mark.

12
00:00:44,499 --> 00:00:45,300
That's incredible.

13
00:00:45,640 --> 00:00:46,983
An absolutely staggering amount.

14
00:00:47,320 --> 00:00:50,984
Check 3: String Octet

15
00:00:51,009 --> 00:00:56,589
This time, Japan Violin, a specialist in top-class string instruments has prepared...

16
00:00:56,614 --> 00:01:01,436
Eight instruments, every single one a world-class masterpiece.

17
00:01:01,461 --> 00:01:03,182
Two violas:

18
00:01:03,207 --> 00:01:06,515
a Domenico Montagnana, 150 million yen,

19
00:01:06,540 --> 00:01:09,777
and a Lorenzo Storioni, 300 million yen.

20
00:01:09,801 --> 00:01:13,994
Cello: the ''Spirito Sorsana'', 90 million yen,

21
00:01:14,021 --> 00:01:17,142
and a Matteo Goffriller, 700 million yen.

22
00:01:17,166 --> 00:01:20,342
Four violins:

23
00:01:20,367 --> 00:01:26,155
first, a Guarneri del Gesù ''Prince Doria'', 2.3 billion yen.

24
00:01:26,180 --> 00:01:32,255
Among the roughly 200 surviving examples in the world, this one is especially prized.

25
00:01:32,280 --> 00:01:35,877
The remaining three are all Stradivarius violins.

26
00:01:36,100 --> 00:01:42,134
A 1727 Stradivarius, 1.8 billion yen.

27
00:01:42,159 --> 00:01:49,243
An important work from Stradivari's highly refined late period.

28
00:01:49,268 --> 00:01:53,915
The Stradivarius ''Kreisler'', 2.4 billion yen.

29
00:01:53,940 --> 00:02:01,074
A rare masterpiece once owned by 20th-century virtuoso Fritz Kreisler, famed for its mature, rounded tone.

30
00:02:01,156 --> 00:02:06,217
And after three years of negotiation, it is finally being shown in Japan for the first time.

31
00:02:06,668 --> 00:02:09,733
The Stradivarius ''Corbett''.

32
00:02:09,759 --> 00:02:11,867
It is worth a program-record...

33
00:02:11,879 --> 00:02:14,384
2.5 billion yen.

34
00:02:14,655 --> 00:02:21,274
Together, these eight instruments produce a sound worth 10.24 billion yen.

35
00:02:21,299 --> 00:02:23,155
And what you'll be comparing that to is...

36
00:02:23,180 --> 00:02:26,128
Instruments used by people who play music as a hobby.

37
00:02:26,160 --> 00:02:27,580
Their total value: 10 million yen.

38
00:02:27,605 --> 00:02:29,313
Even so...

39
00:02:29,387 --> 00:02:30,928
Even so...

40
00:02:31,140 --> 00:02:33,180
It's still 10 million yen.

41
00:02:33,480 --> 00:02:34,495
That's right.

42
00:02:34,674 --> 00:02:37,739
Both the correct and incorrect answers will be played...

43
00:02:38,020 --> 00:02:40,893
...by world-class performers active on the international stage.

44
00:02:41,327 --> 00:02:43,267
Now we'll announce the representatives.

45
00:02:43,292 --> 00:02:45,380
From Team 83 Wins in a Row...

46
00:02:45,460 --> 00:02:46,448
Mr. GACKT.

47
00:02:46,473 --> 00:02:47,835
We're counting on you.

48
00:02:48,420 --> 00:02:50,340
From Team Dendou Emiko...

49
00:02:50,360 --> 00:02:52,415
Ms. Emiko Uemura.

50
00:02:52,440 --> 00:02:53,849
Thank you for taking part.

51
00:02:54,541 --> 00:02:57,435
And these are the rest of the representatives.

52
00:02:57,460 --> 00:02:59,995
A price difference of a thousand times...

53
00:03:00,020 --> 00:03:03,016
There's no way you could get this wrong, right?

54
00:03:03,041 --> 00:03:05,260
All right, representatives, please head to the standby room.

55
00:03:05,260 --> 00:03:06,270
Off you go.

56
00:03:09,289 --> 00:03:10,480
The third check.

57
00:03:10,505 --> 00:03:12,783
What is going to happen?

58
00:03:13,702 --> 00:03:15,525
In the standby room...

59
00:03:15,550 --> 00:03:18,294
They're treated according to their rank.

60
00:03:18,874 --> 00:03:21,923
They treat regular talent badly

61
00:03:21,948 --> 00:03:24,515
usually it's not that bad.

62
00:03:24,827 --> 00:03:28,762
When acting, behind the scenes we use paper cups

63
00:03:28,786 --> 00:03:29,701
Bon appetite...

64
00:03:32,145 --> 00:03:36,300
For this check, several people will listen at the same time.

65
00:03:38,680 --> 00:03:41,706
First, these four pairs will take the test.

66
00:03:42,855 --> 00:03:47,093
Live performances in the studio by top-level musicians.

67
00:03:47,118 --> 00:03:50,977
Everyone at home, please listen along with them.

68
00:03:51,920 --> 00:03:54,574
First, octet A.

69
00:05:20,820 --> 00:05:24,012
Now octet B.

70
00:06:46,653 --> 00:06:52,705
Did you hear the 10.24 billion yen difference?

71
00:06:53,855 --> 00:06:56,332
Who thinks it's A?

72
00:07:01,714 --> 00:07:04,425
So everyone else thinks B?

73
00:07:05,073 --> 00:07:06,459
How do you think it sounded?

74
00:07:06,537 --> 00:07:10,484
Both the low and high notes sounded beautiful

75
00:07:10,534 --> 00:07:12,534
Hiromi also picked B?

76
00:07:12,606 --> 00:07:14,606
I also was listening to the low notes

77
00:07:14,630 --> 00:07:16,165
I thought...

78
00:07:16,202 --> 00:07:18,659
they were very clear

79
00:07:19,550 --> 00:07:22,421
Tendo-san also B?

80
00:07:22,729 --> 00:07:25,023
I think I'll pick A

81
00:07:26,690 --> 00:07:29,546
With the 10.24-billion-yen set,

82
00:07:29,570 --> 00:07:34,946
the sound of the bow hitting the strings, the way it rings out...

83
00:07:34,971 --> 00:07:38,834
well...  you know...

84
00:07:38,846 --> 00:07:44,001
is on a whole different level from newer instruments. The resonance really soars.

85
00:07:44,013 --> 00:07:45,565
I see, yes.

86
00:07:45,657 --> 00:07:49,742
Can Ryoma Takeuchi stay first-class?

87
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:51,345
Here we go.

88
00:07:51,500 --> 00:07:53,606
For question three, you answered B.

89
00:07:53,660 --> 00:07:55,350
Now we'll see if that lines up or not.

90
00:07:55,760 --> 00:07:57,360
Mr. Takeuchi, how are you feeling?

91
00:07:57,720 --> 00:08:00,395
I mean, we get to hear instruments worth 10.24 billion yen, right?

92
00:08:00,420 --> 00:08:01,020
That's right.

93
00:08:01,280 --> 00:08:03,411
I'm actually starting to have fun with this.

94
00:08:03,479 --> 00:08:05,426
You're really enjoying yourself.

95
00:08:05,451 --> 00:08:07,355
In the end, it's an insanely rare sound, isn't it?

96
00:08:07,380 --> 00:08:07,940
Exactly.

97
00:08:08,020 --> 00:08:09,966
So I can just ride that emotion...

98
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:12,395
and pick the right instruments.

99
00:08:12,420 --> 00:08:15,403
So for you this one's easy, then?

100
00:08:15,428 --> 00:08:20,766
Ridiculously easy.

101
00:08:21,133 --> 00:08:22,425
Super easy.

102
00:08:22,455 --> 00:08:24,735
All right, the answer he gave is...

103
00:08:24,760 --> 00:08:25,543
B.

104
00:08:25,680 --> 00:08:27,251
They match.

105
00:08:28,577 --> 00:08:30,656
To me, B...

106
00:08:32,058 --> 00:08:34,063
...sounded more beautiful.

107
00:08:34,200 --> 00:08:36,235
And also, you know...

108
00:08:36,719 --> 00:08:38,772
When it went up into the high notes...

109
00:08:39,270 --> 00:08:41,054
How should I put it...

110
00:08:41,539 --> 00:08:43,055
The ''flavor'' of the sound, I guess?

111
00:08:43,720 --> 00:08:46,582
What is with the way this guy talks? It's annoying.

112
00:08:47,320 --> 00:08:50,335
It's like he's drunk on red wine or something.

113
00:08:50,360 --> 00:08:52,198
He really had quite a bit to drink, you know.

114
00:08:52,620 --> 00:08:54,716
So that great feeling was from the red wine, huh?

115
00:08:54,741 --> 00:08:57,804
Takeuchi goes all in and picks B.

116
00:08:58,980 --> 00:09:00,732
Now, a top-tier artist steps up:

117
00:09:00,840 --> 00:09:02,653
here comes Koda Kumi.

118
00:09:03,240 --> 00:09:04,558
Hmm...I feel like...

119
00:09:04,583 --> 00:09:06,412
(Hiromi-san picked B)

120
00:09:06,579 --> 00:09:08,721
In my 25 years as an artist,

121
00:09:08,779 --> 00:09:09,870
you know, obviously,

122
00:09:09,920 --> 00:09:11,326
I’ve worked with string sections a lot,

123
00:09:11,350 --> 00:09:12,898
and performed with them so many times.

124
00:09:12,989 --> 00:09:15,988
there's no way I will pick the wrong answer

125
00:09:16,013 --> 00:09:20,693
If an actor or a comedian gets this wrong, I think that can’t be helped.

126
00:09:20,718 --> 00:09:25,006
But if a musician misses this, that’s basically grounds for...

127
00:09:25,031 --> 00:09:26,383
retirement.

128
00:09:26,425 --> 00:09:27,542
Retirement!

129
00:09:27,567 --> 00:09:29,277
Whoa, don’t say that!

130
00:09:31,619 --> 00:09:35,067
So what’s the answer she gave, with her career on the line?

131
00:09:35,240 --> 00:09:37,820
The correct answer is B!

132
00:09:38,177 --> 00:09:39,603
They matched

133
00:09:40,112 --> 00:09:46,694
What struck me was just how rich and thick the cello sound was,

134
00:09:46,719 --> 00:09:49,035
and the violins really rang out too.

135
00:09:49,060 --> 00:09:52,625
The sound seemed to soar upward and resonate,

136
00:09:52,760 --> 00:09:56,861
so it almost made the piece itself feel different to me.

137
00:09:56,886 --> 00:09:59,198
This could be retirement

138
00:09:59,223 --> 00:10:04,757
By the way, Go Hiromi, who appeared on the New Year 2022 Kakuzuke Check,

139
00:10:04,769 --> 00:10:07,840
got this one wrong.

140
00:10:08,580 --> 00:10:11,410
Hiromi-san, you are on thin ice with this one.

141
00:10:11,435 --> 00:10:16,148
You’d practically be forced into retirement if you missed it.

142
00:10:16,173 --> 00:10:18,940
With her career at stake, she chose B.

143
00:10:19,200 --> 00:10:23,789
There are battles you simply can’t afford to lose.

144
00:10:24,705 --> 00:10:25,841
I'm relieved

145
00:10:26,595 --> 00:10:29,935
(relieved)

146
00:10:30,020 --> 00:10:32,318
And now, the very ordinary Kansai talent:

147
00:10:32,330 --> 00:10:33,783
Emiko Kaminuma.

148
00:10:34,060 --> 00:10:35,226
Here we go.

149
00:10:37,703 --> 00:10:39,672
I’m really glad I got to do this segment this time.

150
00:10:39,710 --> 00:10:41,625
If Tendo Yoshimi were to get this wrong,

151
00:10:41,650 --> 00:10:42,565
it wouldn’t be a laughing matter.

152
00:10:42,590 --> 00:10:43,875
Because this is about music.

153
00:10:43,900 --> 00:10:46,846
I’ll go with the one that made my inner body tremble.

154
00:10:47,160 --> 00:10:49,668
The one that shook her cells was...

155
00:10:51,980 --> 00:10:54,518
On this you agreed with Tendo-san?

156
00:10:55,888 --> 00:10:59,090
The impact was just on another level.

157
00:10:59,360 --> 00:11:00,960
It hit me right in the gut with a deep boom.

158
00:11:01,860 --> 00:11:04,945
No matter how I think about it, A shook me more.

159
00:11:05,192 --> 00:11:07,600
My heart was trembling.

160
00:11:10,640 --> 00:11:13,875
Emi-chan, with her cells and her heart both quivering,

161
00:11:13,900 --> 00:11:16,464
chooses A, where no one else has gone.

162
00:11:19,370 --> 00:11:20,910
No one.

163
00:11:21,573 --> 00:11:23,128
Nobody.

164
00:11:25,484 --> 00:11:28,135
Going in all alone...

165
00:11:28,160 --> 00:11:29,948
Oh, wow, wow.

166
00:11:30,500 --> 00:11:34,144
Oh man, this is exactly the kind of thing that makes you super anxious.

167
00:11:34,393 --> 00:11:38,035
This is a crucial check for how things go from here.

168
00:11:38,060 --> 00:11:41,067
Is the correct answer A or B?

169
00:11:52,584 --> 00:11:57,274
A total value of the 8 professional instruments is 10.24-billion-yen

170
00:11:57,299 --> 00:11:59,485
Is it A, or is it B?

171
00:11:59,510 --> 00:12:04,223
Now it’s time to reveal the correct answer to everyone in the studio.

172
00:12:05,917 --> 00:12:08,250
All right, the correct answer is...

173
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:11,230
A.

174
00:12:14,633 --> 00:12:16,281
Just you got the right answer

175
00:12:16,323 --> 00:12:19,342
That's right. Astushi please pick correctly!

176
00:12:19,367 --> 00:12:21,367
A made me tremble

177
00:12:22,018 --> 00:12:26,066
She protects the reputation of Kansai talent

178
00:12:27,092 --> 00:12:29,749
Sorry to announce this sad news on New Years...

179
00:12:29,774 --> 00:12:36,088
Koda Kumi will retire today

180
00:12:36,440 --> 00:12:38,557
We must not forget:

181
00:12:38,582 --> 00:12:41,360
Go Hiromi got it wrong again.

182
00:12:41,385 --> 00:12:44,830
Breaking news! Hiromi Go retires!

183
00:12:45,080 --> 00:12:48,643
These guys also absolutely can’t afford to miss it as artists.

184
00:12:48,690 --> 00:12:50,402
The three from Kis-My-Ft2

185
00:12:51,259 --> 00:12:52,732
Please!

186
00:12:53,740 --> 00:12:54,960
Go with A.

187
00:12:56,041 --> 00:12:58,655
The price gap is massive, isn’t it?

188
00:12:58,679 --> 00:13:00,846
So you’d think you’d be able to feel something.

189
00:13:00,871 --> 00:13:02,815
Do you feel it!?

190
00:13:03,520 --> 00:13:05,598
..as an artist.

191
00:13:06,020 --> 00:13:09,685
What do these artists feel? Now in their 15th year?

192
00:13:10,040 --> 00:13:11,263
Ready, set...

193
00:13:12,464 --> 00:13:13,581
Oh no!

194
00:13:14,280 --> 00:13:16,217
A lot of them picked B.

195
00:13:17,238 --> 00:13:18,764
This is bad.

196
00:13:18,952 --> 00:13:20,133
Why, why?

197
00:13:20,300 --> 00:13:23,144
I honestly couldn’t tell which one was better,

198
00:13:23,580 --> 00:13:26,165
but we had that low sound coming from behind us, right?

199
00:13:26,190 --> 00:13:26,829
The cello, yeah.

200
00:13:26,880 --> 00:13:30,776
From the way that sound distorted, I thought this one might have more history to it.

201
00:13:30,801 --> 00:13:32,565
Being 2-to-1 is a disadvantage, you know.

202
00:13:32,620 --> 00:13:33,695
Fukaya-san, I’m counting on you.

203
00:13:33,719 --> 00:13:34,547
Don't give up!

204
00:13:34,860 --> 00:13:38,835
B felt more cohesive overall.

205
00:13:38,860 --> 00:13:40,776
That’s why, for me, A actually felt like

206
00:13:40,801 --> 00:13:43,742
it had more character, like it carried more history.

207
00:13:43,766 --> 00:13:45,695
Yes, yes, yes!

208
00:13:47,259 --> 00:13:48,620
Because I really couldn’t tell.

209
00:13:48,707 --> 00:13:51,472
'A' was more dull, you know? Not so sharp.

210
00:13:51,497 --> 00:13:52,402
Not sharp?

211
00:13:52,427 --> 00:13:56,368
Oh, shut up!

212
00:13:56,660 --> 00:13:58,860
Still, I think it’s B.

213
00:13:58,880 --> 00:14:00,290
I’m going with B. Definitely B.

214
00:14:00,315 --> 00:14:03,244
Wait! Oh no!

215
00:14:04,883 --> 00:14:05,669
B.

216
00:14:07,566 --> 00:14:11,283
Watching it like this really starts to piss me off

217
00:14:11,660 --> 00:14:14,035
Kis-My, who are top class, absolutely perfect...

218
00:14:14,060 --> 00:14:17,920
...head on over to the wrong-answer B room, where all the other hopeless artists are waiting.

219
00:14:22,260 --> 00:14:23,456
Kuri's here!

220
00:14:24,019 --> 00:14:25,566
Yes, he's here! Alright!

221
00:14:25,591 --> 00:14:27,509
Team Artist!

222
00:14:28,344 --> 00:14:33,499
(worried but correct)

223
00:14:33,524 --> 00:14:37,351
Kaminuma-san fainted!

224
00:14:37,376 --> 00:14:39,516
Oh she fell down... are you ok?

225
00:14:41,132 --> 00:14:43,530
I'm going to use all this space

226
00:14:43,555 --> 00:14:46,485
She looks like she's sitting at home

227
00:14:46,576 --> 00:14:48,774
Next up...

228
00:14:48,868 --> 00:14:50,868
 ..these 4 teams

229
00:14:52,809 --> 00:14:56,096
Gakt has to participate in all questions himself

230
00:14:56,121 --> 00:14:58,998
He has lots of pressure

231
00:14:59,023 --> 00:15:05,571
Now, please enjoy the sound of this 10.24-billion-yen instruments

232
00:16:33,980 --> 00:16:36,805
To keep his winning streak alive, we turn to GACKT.

233
00:16:36,830 --> 00:16:37,930
Here we go.

234
00:16:37,955 --> 00:16:39,846
I wonder which one GACKT picked.

235
00:16:40,855 --> 00:16:43,601
Lord GACKT, aiming for his 84th straight win,

236
00:16:43,700 --> 00:16:45,960
how did he work out the answer?

237
00:16:46,972 --> 00:16:50,783
I focused on how much of its character really stood out,

238
00:16:51,580 --> 00:16:52,948
and also,

239
00:16:53,561 --> 00:16:59,062
the strength of the sound right in the Strad's key range,

240
00:16:59,074 --> 00:17:04,790
around 2000 to 6000 Hz,

241
00:17:09,128 --> 00:17:10,911
and the quality of it's attack...

242
00:17:10,936 --> 00:17:11,818
(is he serious?)

243
00:17:12,330 --> 00:17:15,595
...and sustain.

244
00:17:15,620 --> 00:17:18,995
You have to zero in on that balance alone.

245
00:17:19,020 --> 00:17:23,387
If you just listen to the performance and pick the one that sounded better as a performance,

246
00:17:23,411 --> 00:17:25,498
I think you will definitely get it wrong.

247
00:17:25,878 --> 00:17:28,047
Which one did he choose?

248
00:17:28,071 --> 00:17:33,355
Did Lord GACKT ignore the performance and still manage to pick the right one?

249
00:17:33,380 --> 00:17:36,025
(He can see the other rooms on the monitor)...

250
00:17:36,780 --> 00:17:39,324
Yeah, figured as much.

251
00:17:39,349 --> 00:17:41,995
But it must be nice having so many people.

252
00:17:42,020 --> 00:17:44,095
Yeah, being in a big group.

253
00:17:44,120 --> 00:17:45,560
You can actually talk it over.

254
00:17:45,584 --> 00:17:47,413
On your own you do feel a bit insecure.

255
00:17:47,438 --> 00:17:48,801
Yeah, exactly.

256
00:17:51,351 --> 00:17:54,141
This one is tough.

257
00:17:54,520 --> 00:17:56,673
Can he hang on to his top-tier status?

258
00:17:56,700 --> 00:17:58,911
Team Yoshimoto, Atsushi Tamura.

259
00:18:01,360 --> 00:18:04,683
Yeah, I mean, I've been in a band for 20 years too,

260
00:18:04,708 --> 00:18:06,218
That's right.

261
00:18:06,243 --> 00:18:08,001
I've heard all kinds of sounds,

262
00:18:10,317 --> 00:18:11,535
so I think I can tell the difference.

263
00:18:11,560 --> 00:18:15,002
There’s no way our great senior can afford to get this wrong.

264
00:18:15,079 --> 00:18:16,234
The correct answer is...

265
00:18:16,246 --> 00:18:17,456
B.

266
00:18:17,799 --> 00:18:20,245
We’ve got another mismatch here.

267
00:18:20,899 --> 00:18:22,607
Give me a break!

268
00:18:23,001 --> 00:18:24,417
I closed my eyes,

269
00:18:24,979 --> 00:18:28,540
and just gave myself over to every single sound.

270
00:18:30,140 --> 00:18:32,544
And B was the one that made me smile more.

271
00:18:32,569 --> 00:18:35,395
When you feel that warm, gentle quality,

272
00:18:35,420 --> 00:18:37,835
when a sound has that warmth to it,

273
00:18:37,860 --> 00:18:38,700
you just end up smiling.

274
00:18:38,740 --> 00:18:41,328
What on earth are you talking about?

275
00:18:41,353 --> 00:18:46,700
He may have been all smiles, but that top-star aura didn’t help him: off to the wrong-answer B room.

276
00:18:46,725 --> 00:18:49,700
Whoa, seriously?

277
00:18:55,525 --> 00:18:57,555
Kaminuma!

278
00:18:57,580 --> 00:19:00,772
Kaminuma just collapsed!

279
00:19:04,946 --> 00:19:07,549
(Confident but wrong)

280
00:19:07,663 --> 00:19:08,752
Emi-chan is...

281
00:19:08,776 --> 00:19:10,396
We don't know yet

282
00:19:10,459 --> 00:19:12,818
We still don’t know for sure, though.

283
00:19:12,843 --> 00:19:16,902
Ordinary actors: Kimura Tae and Mitsuomi Takahashi.

284
00:19:18,400 --> 00:19:19,611
Alright, we’re up.

285
00:19:20,046 --> 00:19:22,060
We’re counting on you.

286
00:19:22,225 --> 00:19:27,677
When you’re talking 10.2 billion yen, I feel like you don’t hear it anymore, you practically see the sound.

287
00:19:27,702 --> 00:19:28,634
The sound itself.

288
00:19:33,185 --> 00:19:34,772
Hamada-san silent laugh!

289
00:19:34,820 --> 00:19:36,400
Silent!

290
00:19:37,420 --> 00:19:40,305
Did they manage to 'see' the 10.2-billion-yen sound?

291
00:19:40,330 --> 00:19:41,435
What did they answer?

292
00:19:41,610 --> 00:19:42,340
Ready, set...

293
00:19:44,961 --> 00:19:47,250
No split but wrong!

294
00:19:47,275 --> 00:19:48,345
Why?!

295
00:19:48,920 --> 00:19:50,900
They don't need to argue

296
00:19:51,823 --> 00:19:55,132
From the very first note they were completely different.

297
00:19:55,157 --> 00:19:58,080
A felt a bit heavier in terms of weight,

298
00:19:58,103 --> 00:19:59,616
and B felt lighter

299
00:19:59,668 --> 00:20:02,160
Kimura, once we wrap this shoot,

300
00:20:02,160 --> 00:20:05,212
you better go see an ear doctor.

301
00:20:05,237 --> 00:20:05,850
That’s fair, right?

302
00:20:05,920 --> 00:20:08,307
Yeah, fair enough.

303
00:20:09,820 --> 00:20:14,479
For the first time in this studio, we’ve got second-rate celebrities on our hands.

304
00:20:14,504 --> 00:20:19,175
They agreed completely and were full of confidence, only to plummet straight into second-rate status.

305
00:20:19,200 --> 00:20:23,489
Head to the B room, the bug trap for bad ears.

306
00:20:26,180 --> 00:20:27,953
Thank God!

307
00:20:28,760 --> 00:20:29,681
I’m so happy.

308
00:20:30,495 --> 00:20:31,784
Huh?

309
00:20:32,220 --> 00:20:35,500
They’re going to B again

310
00:20:35,822 --> 00:20:42,053
(Reminded of her loneliness from the Wine check)

311
00:20:42,313 --> 00:20:44,400
This is kinda frustrating.

312
00:20:45,740 --> 00:20:48,747
It’s really frustrating.

313
00:20:49,087 --> 00:20:51,087
(Gackt killing time with selfie)

314
00:20:51,112 --> 00:20:58,790
When listening to the sound together, people probably pick ______

315
00:20:58,963 --> 00:21:01,444
First time performing on the Kouhaku Song Festival,

316
00:21:01,500 --> 00:21:04,155
just your average idols.

317
00:21:04,180 --> 00:21:05,870
Alright, this is the last team

318
00:21:06,164 --> 00:21:08,886
Go for it, Fruits Chuck!
(old people call a zipper a "chuck")

319
00:21:08,911 --> 00:21:10,695
We’re 'Zipper'.

320
00:21:10,720 --> 00:21:12,204
It's 'zipper'.

321
00:21:12,527 --> 00:21:15,307
Matsukare actually graduated from a music college.

322
00:21:15,332 --> 00:21:16,280
Matsukare did?

323
00:21:16,920 --> 00:21:18,706
You went to a music college, Matsukare?

324
00:21:18,898 --> 00:21:21,312
You've never told anyone that before.

325
00:21:22,080 --> 00:21:25,360
I mean, I also did classical piano for ten years.

326
00:21:25,610 --> 00:21:26,402
Seriously?

327
00:21:26,430 --> 00:21:29,454
Then it’s hard to decide whose opinion to go with.

328
00:21:30,189 --> 00:21:33,320
Leave it to me too, I think I’ve got a pretty good ear.

329
00:21:33,320 --> 00:21:35,009
She really does have a good ear, so we’re fine.

330
00:21:35,160 --> 00:21:37,596
Oh, this is where you shine?

331
00:21:40,500 --> 00:21:43,068
You haven't done anything yet!

332
00:21:43,093 --> 00:21:46,455
Just trust in my one weapon: my great ear, and go all in.

333
00:21:46,480 --> 00:21:48,407
Because my ears are sharp.

334
00:21:48,748 --> 00:21:50,740
At least wanting to keep regular talent level...

335
00:21:50,820 --> 00:21:52,126
What’s their answer?

336
00:21:52,920 --> 00:21:53,932
Ready, and...

337
00:21:56,480 --> 00:21:57,234
Wait!

338
00:21:57,280 --> 00:21:59,360
Luna, luna, luna...

339
00:21:59,580 --> 00:22:04,440
To me, B sounded tighter and not so light or flimsy.

340
00:22:04,465 --> 00:22:06,525
Because she has a good ear.

341
00:22:06,550 --> 00:22:09,145
Yui-chan is betting everything on that one strength.

342
00:22:09,980 --> 00:22:11,058
Then we’ll go with B.

343
00:22:11,100 --> 00:22:12,849
We choose B.

344
00:22:14,971 --> 00:22:16,465
They went to B!

345
00:22:16,820 --> 00:22:19,237
B.

346
00:22:20,160 --> 00:22:21,423
That was fast.

347
00:22:21,720 --> 00:22:24,316
From today on, why don’t we just call it Fruit Chuck?

348
00:22:24,460 --> 00:22:25,895
I liked 'zipper' better.

349
00:22:25,920 --> 00:22:27,487
It actually has a proper meaning, you know.

350
00:22:27,512 --> 00:22:30,481
From today, 'Fruit Chuck' is officially wrong too.

351
00:22:30,520 --> 00:22:35,590
And with that, lonely little Emiko Kaminuma who waited all by herself has won it all.

352
00:22:36,160 --> 00:22:37,160
Ready, and...

353
00:22:37,550 --> 00:22:39,224
Whoa!

354
00:22:42,040 --> 00:22:43,428
For real?

355
00:22:43,762 --> 00:22:45,737
(the only winner)

356
00:22:45,762 --> 00:22:46,639
Huh?

357
00:22:50,402 --> 00:22:52,037
It’s just Kaminuma-san, all by herself.

358
00:22:52,062 --> 00:22:53,374
Yes I'm by myself.

359
00:22:53,399 --> 00:22:55,941
She really did win it all on her own.

360
00:22:59,798 --> 00:23:02,485
Emiko Kaminuma: a miraculous solo victory!

361
00:23:02,520 --> 00:23:06,985
Coming up: don’t miss Emi-chan crying tears of joy.

362
00:23:09,397 --> 00:23:14,009
The crossroads of fate: time for the results.

363
00:23:14,360 --> 00:23:17,229
All right, here we go.

364
00:23:19,419 --> 00:23:22,768
I'm going to reveal the answer!

365
00:23:23,097 --> 00:23:25,469
Please, go ahead.

366
00:23:25,941 --> 00:23:28,473
I’m scared, I’m scared...

367
00:23:29,262 --> 00:23:31,777
The right answer is...

368
00:23:32,089 --> 00:23:35,594
(futile prayers)

369
00:23:35,994 --> 00:23:39,735
(she will be thrilled!)

370
00:23:44,517 --> 00:23:48,402
Congratulations!

371
00:23:54,221 --> 00:23:56,729
You won by yourself

372
00:23:57,642 --> 00:23:58,783
YA TA!

373
00:23:58,808 --> 00:24:00,672
I'm so happy!

374
00:24:04,329 --> 00:24:06,517
Seriously?

375
00:24:06,630 --> 00:24:09,781
No way

376
00:24:09,806 --> 00:24:11,570
Unexpectedly

377
00:24:14,482 --> 00:24:15,956
happy hug

378
00:24:15,980 --> 00:24:19,558
I’ve never been this happy in my whole life.

379
00:24:19,919 --> 00:24:22,060
Yes!

380
00:24:22,500 --> 00:24:24,218
I did it!

381
00:24:24,281 --> 00:24:25,556
I’m so happy.

382
00:24:25,700 --> 00:24:28,300
Nothing could make me happier ... at this age

383
00:24:28,820 --> 00:24:34,648
Kaminuma-san is in tears.

384
00:24:34,673 --> 00:24:37,515
Now everyone, we have some sad news.

385
00:24:37,540 --> 00:24:39,177
This year, Kumi Koda will be retiring.

386
00:24:39,202 --> 00:24:41,680
Stop it!

387
00:24:41,705 --> 00:24:44,276
Seriously?

388
00:24:44,583 --> 00:24:48,728
A huge upset in the 8 string orchestra

389
00:24:48,753 --> 00:24:53,825
Did Lord Gackt manage to pick the correct answer, A?

390
00:24:54,640 --> 00:24:58,638
At the crossroads of fate: Gackt’s answer revealed.

391
00:24:59,200 --> 00:25:04,007
All right, I’m sure GAKU-chan is in this one too.

392
00:25:04,359 --> 00:25:08,773
Now, I’ll open the door to the correct room.

393
00:25:18,139 --> 00:25:20,511
Shaaa!

394
00:25:24,789 --> 00:25:26,997
Brilliant—84 wins in a row!

395
00:25:27,083 --> 00:25:29,157
That’s insane.

396
00:25:30,662 --> 00:25:34,099
Even I was a little unsure.

397
00:25:34,140 --> 00:25:38,115
Each part was so strong on its own that together it sounded kind of rough.

398
00:25:38,140 --> 00:25:42,641
But if you listen to each element, A is overwhelmingly stronger.

399
00:25:43,560 --> 00:25:46,395
He somehow cleared the question he was worried about.

400
00:25:46,420 --> 00:25:50,215
The unstoppable Lord Gackt’s winning streak is now at 84.

401
00:25:50,976 --> 00:25:53,765
With this, Lord Gackt is the only top-tier celebrity left.

402
00:25:53,790 --> 00:25:57,359
Why does it always end up like this?

403
00:25:57,371 --> 00:25:59,090
Try a little harder

404
00:25:59,146 --> 00:26:02,475
Our two correct answerers have returned.

405
00:26:02,500 --> 00:26:09,279
84straight wins, and Kaminuma-sama’s three-years-in-the-making revenge is complete.

406
00:26:10,235 --> 00:26:11,694
Excellent!

407
00:26:11,719 --> 00:26:14,016
Impressive, impressive, truly impressive.

408
00:26:14,040 --> 00:26:18,314
Now, everyone who got it wrong, please proceed to pay your respects.

409
00:26:19,516 --> 00:26:26,208
Our wrong answerers will enter to a performance by staff who has never taken a single violin lesson.

410
00:26:28,040 --> 00:26:29,995
Wow, what an incredible sound...

411
00:26:30,020 --> 00:26:32,297
Oh man, what is this?

412
00:26:38,539 --> 00:26:41,804
Our wrong answerers have returned.

413
00:26:48,534 --> 00:26:50,778
Everyone is back.

414
00:26:50,920 --> 00:26:51,880
We were totally confident.

415
00:26:51,910 --> 00:26:54,253
Atsushi!

416
00:26:54,401 --> 00:26:57,514
Please disband your band immediately.

417
00:26:58,483 --> 00:27:01,418
Uh, this is Koda-san, right?

418
00:27:01,568 --> 00:27:02,357
I’m Koda

419
00:27:02,438 --> 00:27:03,575
Nice to be working with you.

420
00:27:03,610 --> 00:27:04,749
So from today you will...

421
00:27:04,774 --> 00:27:07,338
No, no, no, that was staff’s twisting our arm

422
00:27:07,365 --> 00:27:09,561
No we didn't.

423
00:27:11,140 --> 00:27:14,415
Fruit chuck.

424
00:27:14,440 --> 00:27:17,402
You were really full of confidence too, though.

425
00:27:17,427 --> 00:27:21,439
I learned a lot from that.

426
00:27:23,410 --> 00:27:25,422
All right, let’s move on. Time for the next check.

427
00:27:25,980 --> 00:27:27,479
Here is the fourth check.

428
00:27:27,504 --> 00:27:31,447
Check 4: Michelin Chef

429
00:27:31,680 --> 00:27:36,475
The Michelin Guide is globally renowned and trusted for rating restaurants.

430
00:27:36,500 --> 00:27:39,958
This time, you’ll have to identify the chef from a restaurant

431
00:27:39,983 --> 00:27:45,238
that has held one Michelin star for eight years in a row.

432
00:27:45,263 --> 00:27:47,520
This is the Michelin-starred chef is...

433
00:27:47,544 --> 00:27:51,316
Chef Ippei Matsumoto of L’ape in Nihonbashi, Tokyo.

434
00:27:51,340 --> 00:27:54,673
Check 4: Michelin Chef.

435
00:27:54,697 --> 00:28:02,375
L’ape, a famous restaurant in Nihonbashi, Tokyo, with one Michelin star for eight straight years.

436
00:28:02,400 --> 00:28:08,835
Owner-chef Ippei Matsumoto specializes in modern French cuisine.

437
00:28:08,860 --> 00:28:14,823
He blends classic French cooking with seasonal Japanese ingredients.

438
00:28:15,260 --> 00:28:23,269
His seasonal menus bring out the full natural flavor of each ingredient.

439
00:28:24,169 --> 00:28:29,438
This challenge features two Western favorites: beef stew

440
00:28:30,680 --> 00:28:33,545
and doria.

441
00:28:34,252 --> 00:28:39,617
Chef Matsumoto, with his one Michelin star, prepared the dishes for us.

442
00:28:39,642 --> 00:28:41,986
And here are the people we’ll be comparing him with.

443
00:28:42,011 --> 00:28:45,495
The Sato brothers from Ox in Nippori, Tokyo.

444
00:28:45,520 --> 00:28:49,335
Chef Tadao Sato and his younger brother, Chef Eiji.

445
00:28:49,360 --> 00:28:52,365
Their signature dish is their mixed-fry set meal.

446
00:28:52,390 --> 00:28:54,599
That looks delicious.

447
00:28:54,783 --> 00:29:01,568
Ox is a long-standing Western-style restaurant that has been beloved by locals for over 50 years.

448
00:29:01,760 --> 00:29:03,475
The ones who have kept that flavor alive are

449
00:29:03,500 --> 00:29:07,158
the elder brother, 82-year-old Chef Tadao,

450
00:29:07,170 --> 00:29:11,264
and his 73-year-old younger brother, Chef Eiji.

451
00:29:11,289 --> 00:29:18,323
For reference, we had the two brothers taste the correct Michelin dishes beforehand.

452
00:29:18,791 --> 00:29:20,215
delicious

453
00:29:20,240 --> 00:29:22,944
excellent!

454
00:29:22,969 --> 00:29:26,540
It's good but our food is better

455
00:29:26,574 --> 00:29:28,574
Agreed

456
00:29:28,599 --> 00:29:30,829
We can do it

457
00:29:30,880 --> 00:29:32,635
By the way, as for the doria,

458
00:29:32,660 --> 00:29:34,572
it’s not actually on their menu,

459
00:29:34,597 --> 00:29:37,400
so they made doria for the first time since the restaurant opened.

460
00:29:38,860 --> 00:29:41,295
Now then, everyone, this particular challenge

461
00:29:41,320 --> 00:29:43,820
is a three-way choice: A, B, or C.

462
00:29:43,848 --> 00:29:48,980
So unlike usual, this check has A, B, and also C.

463
00:29:49,988 --> 00:29:54,700
And one of them is a chef so bad that picking him would be downright embarrassing as a human being.

464
00:29:55,280 --> 00:29:56,795
Here is that chef.

465
00:29:58,340 --> 00:30:00,215
You all know who it is already, right?

466
00:30:00,240 --> 00:30:05,855
It’s Master of Gakuzuke Check, cooking amateur, Chef Masatoshi Hamada.

467
00:30:05,880 --> 00:30:07,676
He’s so awkward, isn’t he?

468
00:30:08,239 --> 00:30:09,666
That’s way too much.

469
00:30:09,740 --> 00:30:11,575
You’re just dumping it in at random.

470
00:30:11,600 --> 00:30:13,617
You’re going to kill all the flavor.

471
00:30:14,020 --> 00:30:21,719
That said, he really went all in this time, starting the beef stew five days ago and simmering it for days.

472
00:30:21,744 --> 00:30:26,355
For the doria, he just quickly checked a recipe on YouTube right before recording

473
00:30:26,380 --> 00:30:29,695
and whipped it up on the spot.

474
00:30:29,720 --> 00:30:33,020
Even though Chef Hamada is an amateur,

475
00:30:33,260 --> 00:30:40,672
he does have a record of fooling the taste buds of 36 top celebrities so far.

476
00:30:40,697 --> 00:30:43,575
Of course, if you choose the absolutely-no-good Chef Hamada,

477
00:30:43,600 --> 00:30:46,611
your rank will drop by two levels.

478
00:30:47,714 --> 00:30:48,795
That’s only fair.

479
00:30:48,820 --> 00:30:50,190
Exactly.

480
00:30:50,215 --> 00:30:52,540
All right, everyone, please move to the next area.

481
00:30:52,800 --> 00:30:55,220
This will be a check for all of you.

482
00:30:55,245 --> 00:30:59,757
Work it out together nicely, without fighting, and come to an answer.

483
00:31:03,995 --> 00:31:07,152
First up, the team that was in tears after a solo victory earlier,

484
00:31:07,220 --> 00:31:09,667
and managed to stay at the rank of Ordinary Celebrity.

485
00:31:09,692 --> 00:31:14,973
Team Tendo & Emiko, with over 100 years of showbiz experience between them.

486
00:31:15,139 --> 00:31:16,908
Yes, I’ll definitely be able to tell.

487
00:31:16,933 --> 00:31:17,845
You can tell, right?

488
00:31:17,870 --> 00:31:18,743
Yes, I can.

489
00:31:18,768 --> 00:31:23,675
I’ve hosted a cooking talk show here for 27 years,

490
00:31:23,700 --> 00:31:26,295
and I’ve done about 200 dishes on YouTube as well.

491
00:31:26,320 --> 00:31:28,086
All cooked by myself.

492
00:31:29,010 --> 00:31:30,815
Just leave this to me.

493
00:31:30,840 --> 00:31:33,235
She got the last one right all by herself,

494
00:31:33,800 --> 00:31:36,828
I'm in a great mood now.

495
00:31:36,853 --> 00:31:41,135
This time we have a special rule: beef stew and doria,

496
00:31:41,160 --> 00:31:44,469
and each member in a team will eat a different one.

497
00:31:44,595 --> 00:31:46,824
So, what are you having?

498
00:31:47,440 --> 00:31:49,604
I’ll have the beef stew.

499
00:31:50,380 --> 00:31:52,833
I’ll have the doria.

500
00:31:53,394 --> 00:31:55,947
The Michelin chef’s beef stew

501
00:31:55,972 --> 00:32:00,660
luxuriously uses Tokachi Herb Beef, a premium brand from Hokkaido.

502
00:32:01,640 --> 00:32:04,780
It’s based on a veal stock made from beef bones,

503
00:32:04,800 --> 00:32:09,880
then slowly simmered for three days with meat, aromatic vegetables, red wine, and more,

504
00:32:10,340 --> 00:32:13,369
creating a dish packed with concentrated umami.

505
00:32:14,020 --> 00:32:19,976
The doria uses Daisen chicken from Tottori, known for its rich, flavorful fat.

506
00:32:20,740 --> 00:32:25,829
Rice cooked in chicken broth is topped with a béchamel sauce

507
00:32:26,020 --> 00:32:28,333
that’s packed with concentrated chicken flavor.

508
00:32:28,483 --> 00:32:33,248
The refined taste of the chicken fills your mouth with flavor.

509
00:32:33,418 --> 00:32:37,640
While the ingredients are slightly different,

510
00:32:38,100 --> 00:32:43,728
you can try similar dishes at Lapetit, a bistro in the same restaurant group run by Chef Matsumoto.

511
00:32:47,494 --> 00:32:49,791
It doesn’t feel out of place at all.

512
00:32:50,645 --> 00:32:51,668
Yes it does

513
00:32:53,120 --> 00:32:55,450
First, beef stew A.

514
00:32:56,760 --> 00:32:58,089
How are you going to eat?

515
00:32:58,509 --> 00:33:01,575
Open your mouth.

516
00:33:01,600 --> 00:33:02,880
I’ll open my mouth.

517
00:33:03,760 --> 00:33:07,600
Ueno has hosted a cooking show for 27 years.

518
00:33:07,940 --> 00:33:10,749
She absolutely wants to get this one right.

519
00:33:12,140 --> 00:33:14,055
Meanwhile, Tendo is in charge of the doria.

520
00:33:14,080 --> 00:33:18,653
Can she redeem herself after being the sole loser on the wine check?

521
00:33:19,940 --> 00:33:21,836
Next up is B.

522
00:33:25,920 --> 00:33:29,325
All you have to do is pick the real Michelin chef.

523
00:33:30,120 --> 00:33:33,690
 If you pick Hamada’s cooking and drop two ranks,

524
00:33:33,702 --> 00:33:38,262
it’s basically like telling the whole world you’ve got a dumb tongue.

525
00:33:41,799 --> 00:33:43,023
She's really chomping away.

526
00:33:45,582 --> 00:33:47,902
You two are impressive.

527
00:33:49,000 --> 00:33:50,720
And the answer they chose is...

528
00:33:50,840 --> 00:33:52,013
Ready... go!

529
00:33:53,940 --> 00:33:56,667
They matched.

530
00:33:56,693 --> 00:33:58,257
Such tender meat.

531
00:33:58,281 --> 00:33:59,335
The sauce was...

532
00:33:59,360 --> 00:34:01,502
seasoned just right, you know?

533
00:34:01,527 --> 00:34:04,120
It's mellow, with a really rich depth of flavor.

534
00:34:04,700 --> 00:34:07,482
You get that hit of umami, like, 'wow, this is good.'

535
00:34:08,680 --> 00:34:09,480
I'm going with A.

536
00:34:09,500 --> 00:34:11,599
Our choice is A.

537
00:34:11,860 --> 00:34:14,100
Hamada, how many people do you think you can fool?

538
00:34:14,100 --> 00:34:14,886
No idea.

539
00:34:14,911 --> 00:34:18,056
When it comes to this, though, I am pretty confident.

540
00:34:18,820 --> 00:34:22,730
Their answers match: Team Emiko Tendo chooses A.

541
00:34:23,440 --> 00:34:25,775
Yeah, I think we did pretty well with that.

542
00:34:25,997 --> 00:34:33,004
But what happens next is completely unexpected.

543
00:34:35,378 --> 00:34:39,610
Michelin Check: next up, the regular actors.

544
00:34:39,777 --> 00:34:41,142
We should be fine.

545
00:34:41,580 --> 00:34:43,376
As long as we don't pick Hamada's.

546
00:34:43,401 --> 00:34:44,415
We won't pick his.

547
00:34:47,051 --> 00:34:48,995
I actually want you to pick mine, though.

548
00:34:49,020 --> 00:34:50,566
The dish is...

549
00:34:50,980 --> 00:34:52,710
Beef stew.

550
00:34:52,860 --> 00:34:54,448
Doria

551
00:34:54,840 --> 00:34:57,282
What about this one, I wonder.

552
00:34:57,757 --> 00:34:59,696
It doesn't feel out of place at all.

553
00:35:00,700 --> 00:35:02,236
Yeah, totally natural.

554
00:35:02,620 --> 00:35:05,336
Good morning.

555
00:35:05,880 --> 00:35:08,020
These two have a certain air of elegance about them.

556
00:35:08,040 --> 00:35:11,197
Even the way they eat looks refined.

557
00:35:12,180 --> 00:35:14,756
For the sake of the new drama that's about to start,

558
00:35:14,781 --> 00:35:17,474
